If SCOTUS ever actually writes a reasoned judgment on the dissolution of the US government (as opposed to the judgment by post-it you've had for the last year), you may expect it to be 'en banc' -- i.e., heard by all nine judges. Note that this does not mean that all judges will share in the same reasons. A case heard 'en banc' may be decided 9-0, 5-4, or even 1-1-1-1-1-1-1-1-1, if each judge writes their  own opinion (heaven forfend!) 
I am advised that, at least in Canada, the justices strive mightily to find common ground and so to write common reasons to be shared by several judges, for the better clarity of the decision.

